1
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:35,510
The end of the Arctic summer,

2
00:00:35,600 --> 00:00:38,310
and the sun hasn't set for three months.

3
00:00:38,920 --> 00:00:42,550
It's hard to imagine the bitter cold
will soon return.

4
00:00:53,520 --> 00:00:56,310
Some will welcome the chills of autumn,

5
00:00:56,400 --> 00:01:01,630
but for most, time is running out before
they will have to retreat to the south.

6
00:01:11,600 --> 00:01:14,470
Early autumn in the Canadian Arctic

7
00:01:14,560 --> 00:01:17,310
and polar bears are gathering
on the coastal strip,

8
00:01:17,400 --> 00:01:19,590
waiting for the sea to freeze.

9
00:01:28,160 --> 00:01:33,670
But a life spent alone on the sea-ice
is no preparation for a crowded beach.

10
00:01:35,720 --> 00:01:39,350
Such close contact with other bears
must be stressful.

11
00:01:39,440 --> 00:01:41,150
Surely tempers will flare.

12
00:01:47,880 --> 00:01:50,870
Over half a tonne of bear
slams into the other.

13
00:02:09,040 --> 00:02:13,870
Polar bears will fight to the death
over mates, but not in autumn.

14
00:02:15,200 --> 00:02:17,830
Now these fearsome predators display

15
00:02:17,920 --> 00:02:20,910
a surprisingly tolerant side
to their natures.

16
00:02:22,960 --> 00:02:26,950
Being marooned on land
means the bears no longer have access

17
00:02:27,040 --> 00:02:29,310
to the seals they usually hunt

18
00:02:29,400 --> 00:02:32,750
and they have to scrape by
on whatever they can find.

19
00:02:34,640 --> 00:02:38,230
Like bears the world over,
they're not choosy feeders.

20
00:02:39,120 --> 00:02:41,070
They even turn vegetarian,

21
00:02:41,160 --> 00:02:44,630
delicately picking out berries
from between the thorns.

22
00:02:55,200 --> 00:02:56,950
There are plenty to go around,

23
00:02:57,040 --> 00:02:59,790
so there's no need
to squabble over them.

24
00:03:03,400 --> 00:03:05,630
Any fighting is just for fun.

25
00:03:19,240 --> 00:03:22,590
The bears select sparring partners
who are well-matched

26
00:03:22,680 --> 00:03:24,550
and they always pull their punches.

27
00:03:24,640 --> 00:03:27,510
No one wants to get hurt
in a play-fight.

28
00:03:58,320 --> 00:04:01,870
Perhaps these bouts
are a way of testing rivals

29
00:04:01,960 --> 00:04:05,070
in case they ever meet again
out on the sea-ice.

30
00:04:08,080 --> 00:04:09,350
One thing's for sure,

31
00:04:09,440 --> 00:04:14,950
the famous loners are revealing
a social, playful side we rarely see.

32
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:30,230
It's all just boisterous fun,

33
00:04:30,320 --> 00:04:32,430
but with so many big males around,

34
00:04:32,520 --> 00:04:35,790
the females keep their cubs
at a safe distance.

35
00:04:59,360 --> 00:05:04,030
The wary mother will lead her young
to a quieter beach along the coast

36
00:05:04,120 --> 00:05:06,870
while she waits for the ocean to freeze.

37
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:21,670
The sea-ice is now
at its minimum extent.

38
00:05:22,720 --> 00:05:25,750
In the Canadian Arctic,
vast stretches of coastline

39
00:05:25,840 --> 00:05:29,470
are now unlocked
and ready to receive visitors.

40
00:05:36,880 --> 00:05:40,510
Belugas, the white whales of the north.

41
00:05:42,240 --> 00:05:46,510
They're relying on open water
to reach an ancient rendezvous.

42
00:05:50,200 --> 00:05:54,270
It's a journey they make every year
along traditional routes.

43
00:06:21,720 --> 00:06:24,070
Baby belugas ride piggy-back,

44
00:06:24,320 --> 00:06:27,150
pulled along
by their mother's slipstream.

45
00:06:28,840 --> 00:06:31,190
This one is only a month old,

46
00:06:31,280 --> 00:06:34,150
and won't turn white
for another five years.

47
00:06:45,040 --> 00:06:47,790
Thousands of belugas are being drawn

48
00:06:47,880 --> 00:06:51,310
to one special estuary
in the Canadian Arctic.

49
00:07:00,080 --> 00:07:02,590
It isn't food that brings them here.

50
00:07:05,280 --> 00:07:08,550
Curiously, it's personal hygiene.

51
00:07:12,360 --> 00:07:15,590
When the tide is low,
they swim into the shallows

52
00:07:15,680 --> 00:07:18,670
and flail around with great enthusiasm.

53
00:07:28,280 --> 00:07:30,990
They're after a body scrub.

54
00:07:39,160 --> 00:07:41,070
The gravel acts as a loofah

55
00:07:41,160 --> 00:07:45,590
and thrashing their bodies across it
helps to get rid of their old skin.

56
00:07:48,480 --> 00:07:51,670
Presumably the treatment keeps them
clean and streamlined.

57
00:07:52,240 --> 00:07:54,390
But it also appears to feel good.

58
00:08:10,400 --> 00:08:11,670
Bliss!

59
00:08:18,680 --> 00:08:22,030
The water in the estuary is warmer
and less salty

60
00:08:22,120 --> 00:08:26,350
and that seems to soften the skin,
making the scrub more effective.

61
00:08:54,800 --> 00:08:59,510
This secluded estuary
is only a temporary whale spa.

62
00:08:59,600 --> 00:09:04,430
The ocean will soon freeze again,
forcing the whales to travel south.

63
00:09:13,920 --> 00:09:18,750
Vast seabird colonies
are the jewels of the Arctic.

64
00:09:31,200 --> 00:09:34,110
BrÃ¼nnich guillemots have
spent the summer months

65
00:09:34,200 --> 00:09:38,510
packed together on vertical cliffs
beyond the reach of predators.

66
00:09:47,960 --> 00:09:51,630
They are among the most numerous
seabirds in the Northern Hemisphere.

67
00:09:51,720 --> 00:09:55,910
This colony alone contains 100, 000 birds

68
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:59,910
and there are many more like it
all along the Arctic coastline.

69
00:10:05,320 --> 00:10:09,030
In just a few weeks,
these cliffs will empty,

70
00:10:09,120 --> 00:10:12,950
but before the guillemots can leave,
their chicks must fledge.

71
00:10:13,760 --> 00:10:15,870
Their feathers are now fully formed,

72
00:10:15,960 --> 00:10:20,110
but their stubby wings are still
too short for them to fly properly.

73
00:10:20,800 --> 00:10:22,790
This will be a challenge.

74
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:29,590
It's a 150-metre drop

75
00:10:29,680 --> 00:10:32,790
and they need to make it
all the way to the sea.

76
00:10:34,800 --> 00:10:36,110
Here goes.

77
00:10:45,480 --> 00:10:48,830
He falls short
and survives the crash landing.

78
00:10:54,760 --> 00:10:59,070
The chicks are manna from heaven
for an Arctic fox.

79
00:11:04,240 --> 00:11:07,070
The next chick is accompanied
by a parent.

80
00:11:18,960 --> 00:11:20,550
Failed again.

81
00:11:27,920 --> 00:11:29,630
This looks better.

82
00:11:44,920 --> 00:11:46,270
Success!

83
00:11:48,560 --> 00:11:51,110
Aquatic landings are certainly gentler

84
00:11:51,200 --> 00:11:53,670
and foxes can't reach you out here.

85
00:11:56,640 --> 00:12:01,190
The chicks will stay in
their parents' care for another month.

86
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:15,350
The guillemots are not
the only ones preparing to leave.

87
00:12:16,040 --> 00:12:19,510
All across the Arctic,
millions of summer visitors

88
00:12:19,600 --> 00:12:22,030
are beginning to return south.

89
00:12:46,960 --> 00:12:49,510
The guillemot chicks can't fly yet,

90
00:12:49,600 --> 00:12:53,830
so they and their families must swim
to their winter feeding grounds.

91
00:12:55,720 --> 00:13:00,310
It's a journey that will take them
a thousand miles south to the open ocean

92
00:13:00,400 --> 00:13:02,830
and away from the approaching ice.

93
00:13:08,640 --> 00:13:14,070
The breeding season is over
and silence returns to the Arctic.

94
00:13:21,520 --> 00:13:24,310
But as the first storms of autumn

95
00:13:24,400 --> 00:13:26,790
sweep through
the deserted nesting grounds,

96
00:13:26,880 --> 00:13:30,990
they bring an unexpected bonanza
for the few that remain.

97
00:13:39,720 --> 00:13:42,790
The discovery doesn't
remain secret for long.

98
00:13:53,960 --> 00:13:56,830
It's a huge fin whale carcass.

99
00:13:57,800 --> 00:14:00,910
The polar bears have been drawn
from several miles away,

100
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:03,990
guided by their extraordinary sense
of smell.

101
00:14:06,600 --> 00:14:08,830
Bears are arriving all the time,

102
00:14:08,920 --> 00:14:12,830
but there's plenty of room
at this 18-metre long dining table.

103
00:14:18,920 --> 00:14:20,990
They're surprisingly relaxed,

104
00:14:21,080 --> 00:14:24,590
but with enough for everyone,
there's no need to argue.

105
00:14:29,200 --> 00:14:32,670
The tastiest morsels
are often underwater.

106
00:14:46,040 --> 00:14:49,390
Others prefer some greens
with their dinner.

107
00:15:13,960 --> 00:15:16,350
After a well-balanced meal,

108
00:15:16,440 --> 00:15:19,470
there's nothing better
than some good company.

109
00:15:38,840 --> 00:15:41,230
Despite their reputation as loners,

110
00:15:41,320 --> 00:15:44,990
it's surprising
just how sociable polar bears can be.

111
00:16:06,920 --> 00:16:10,950
All across the Arctic,
the temperature is now dropping

112
00:16:11,040 --> 00:16:13,750
and the sea is beginning to freeze.

113
00:16:14,400 --> 00:16:19,350
Every day over 20,000 square miles
of ocean turn to ice

114
00:16:19,440 --> 00:16:21,030
as the cold spreads south.

115
00:16:26,720 --> 00:16:31,230
At first, a thin, greasy film
appears on the surface.

116
00:16:44,040 --> 00:16:48,030
Next, pancakes of ice start to appear.

117
00:17:08,480 --> 00:17:13,030
The pancakes lock together
and form a continuous sheet.

118
00:17:23,120 --> 00:17:26,590
The Arctic Ocean is freezing again.

119
00:17:35,960 --> 00:17:41,990
At last, the bear family can return
to the sea-ice, where they belong.

120
00:17:53,560 --> 00:17:58,270
It's been six months since
the cubs first emerged from the den.

121
00:18:00,720 --> 00:18:04,310
They've survived the hazards
of melting sea-ice in spring

122
00:18:04,400 --> 00:18:06,430
and lack of food in summer,

123
00:18:06,520 --> 00:18:10,310
and now, at last,
they are in their element again.

124
00:18:16,120 --> 00:18:19,910
As the north of our planet
turns away from the sun,

125
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:22,670
the big chill travels south.

126
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:31,030
Temperatures on the tundra
start to fall.

127
00:18:33,840 --> 00:18:38,150
The shorter days and colder nights
trigger a dramatic change

128
00:18:38,240 --> 00:18:40,750
in the willows and blueberry bushes.

129
00:18:41,040 --> 00:18:45,150
They stop producing the green pigment
that harnesses the sun's energy.

130
00:18:45,240 --> 00:18:48,470
And red and yellow pigments
build up in their leaves.

131
00:19:03,440 --> 00:19:08,630
The tundra blazes with colour
and the whole landscape is transformed.

132
00:19:23,080 --> 00:19:28,470
A bull musk ox marks his territory
with scent from the glands on his face.

133
00:19:28,840 --> 00:19:31,510
He's preparing for the breeding season.

134
00:19:33,840 --> 00:19:36,190
He shadows his harem of females

135
00:19:36,280 --> 00:19:39,590
as they graze the last
of the summer grasses.

136
00:19:44,400 --> 00:19:46,350
He must be on his guard.

137
00:19:50,360 --> 00:19:52,150
An outsider is arriving,

138
00:19:52,240 --> 00:19:55,390
a large male
whose intentions soon become clear.

139
00:20:01,240 --> 00:20:04,550
The newcomer circles
the resident bull warily.

140
00:20:06,520 --> 00:20:09,550
The resident must take up
the intruder's challenge.

141
00:20:34,520 --> 00:20:39,830
This clash of polar Titans could
easily become a fight to the death.

142
00:20:51,840 --> 00:20:55,950
The impact is like a car crash
at 30 miles an hour.

143
00:21:18,720 --> 00:21:22,270
A heavy skull
and a helmet of horn four inches thick

144
00:21:22,360 --> 00:21:25,990
provide some protection
for the musk ox's brain.

145
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:44,590
Over the next half hour,
the advantage ebbs and flows,

146
00:21:44,680 --> 00:21:47,590
as each tries to finish the duel.

147
00:21:47,680 --> 00:21:50,710
If one can turn the other
and gore its flank,

148
00:21:50,800 --> 00:21:52,710
the fight will be over.

149
00:22:02,840 --> 00:22:07,910
The stakes rise as the risk of injury
or even death increases.

150
00:22:20,080 --> 00:22:22,270
The rival is out-manoeuvred.

151
00:22:24,840 --> 00:22:28,310
And the champion returns to his females.

152
00:22:36,520 --> 00:22:39,950
By now, most animals
have migrated south,

153
00:22:40,040 --> 00:22:43,470
but the musk oxen
with their thick coats will stay

154
00:22:43,560 --> 00:22:45,870
and face the approaching winter.

155
00:22:56,160 --> 00:22:57,990
As autumn progresses,

156
00:22:58,080 --> 00:23:03,350
the moisture in the air freezes
and hoarfrost decorates the leaves.

157
00:23:33,960 --> 00:23:38,270
Ice crystals grow like diamonds
on every twig.

158
00:23:54,080 --> 00:23:59,270
All across the tundra, both the rivers
and the ground freeze solid.

159
00:24:29,640 --> 00:24:35,870
Glassy cathedrals form, as the remaining
water becomes locked up as ice.

160
00:24:41,680 --> 00:24:46,510
Soon, even the largest waterfalls
will be motionless.

161
00:24:51,800 --> 00:24:55,390
The tundra has been transformed
once again.

162
00:24:55,480 --> 00:24:57,270
It appears deserted.

163
00:25:03,200 --> 00:25:05,510
Caribou on their migration.

164
00:25:07,120 --> 00:25:11,070
Unlike the musk ox,
caribou do head south for the winter,

165
00:25:11,480 --> 00:25:14,110
but it's a long and difficult journey.

166
00:25:16,040 --> 00:25:18,790
They use the frozen lakes as ice roads.

167
00:25:18,880 --> 00:25:21,230
These are flat and firm,

168
00:25:21,320 --> 00:25:25,750
but it seems hooves and ice
were never really meant to go together.

169
00:25:34,720 --> 00:25:37,430
The frisky males would be well-advised

170
00:25:37,520 --> 00:25:41,950
to keep at least one eye on the road
as the mating season begins.

171
00:25:56,800 --> 00:26:00,830
A cow is being closely guarded
by a mature bull,

172
00:26:00,920 --> 00:26:03,110
with his much larger antlers.

173
00:26:10,600 --> 00:26:13,070
The females are busy feeding up
for the winter,

174
00:26:13,560 --> 00:26:16,390
but the bull has other things
on his mind.

175
00:26:18,800 --> 00:26:21,270
The cow is playing hard to get.

176
00:26:22,320 --> 00:26:24,790
She heads off with her admirer
in pursuit.

177
00:26:36,320 --> 00:26:39,030
Several other bulls join in the chase.

178
00:26:52,080 --> 00:26:53,350
She's out in front,

179
00:26:53,440 --> 00:26:56,190
but the amorous males
are gaining on her.

180
00:27:05,320 --> 00:27:09,030
The big bull breaks off his chase
to deal with a rival.

181
00:27:11,880 --> 00:27:15,070
But now he's fallen behind
the other challengers.

182
00:27:23,240 --> 00:27:25,470
The younger bulls,
with their lighter antlers,

183
00:27:25,560 --> 00:27:27,510
keep up with the cow more easily,

184
00:27:27,600 --> 00:27:31,750
but as the pace slows,
the older bull catches up.

185
00:27:32,040 --> 00:27:34,310
Again he has to stop and fight.

186
00:28:00,200 --> 00:28:03,630
A decisive victory for the big male.

187
00:28:04,560 --> 00:28:07,270
He's earned the respect
of the vanquished bulls

188
00:28:07,360 --> 00:28:09,510
and they now trail in his wake.

189
00:28:11,040 --> 00:28:14,550
It's now become a game
of Grandma's Footsteps.

190
00:28:15,280 --> 00:28:17,270
One look from the boss

191
00:28:19,080 --> 00:28:21,950
and the young-bloods freeze
in their tracks.

192
00:28:30,680 --> 00:28:33,550
The exhausted bull guards his prize,

193
00:28:33,640 --> 00:28:38,270
but he'll need to recover before he is
able to make the most of his victory.

194
00:28:39,200 --> 00:28:41,910
And the herd continues its journey south

195
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:44,790
to avoid the worst
of the advancing cold.

196
00:28:57,360 --> 00:28:59,430
From the ocean to the tundra,

197
00:28:59,520 --> 00:29:02,670
the north of our planet
is now completely frozen.

198
00:29:08,440 --> 00:29:10,350
The Antarctic.

199
00:29:10,440 --> 00:29:11,950
In the far south,

200
00:29:12,040 --> 00:29:16,830
autumn can be a particularly savage
and unpredictable time.

201
00:29:21,160 --> 00:29:23,790
South Georgia is a splinter of rock

202
00:29:23,880 --> 00:29:26,670
in the middle
of the vast Southern Ocean.

203
00:29:26,760 --> 00:29:30,990
It's only 100 miles long
and is battered by the elements.

204
00:29:38,040 --> 00:29:41,830
This ocean generates some of
the largest waves on the planet.

205
00:29:42,040 --> 00:29:45,630
They gain size and power
as they travel around the globe,

206
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:50,030
uninterrupted by land for 12,000 miles.

207
00:29:53,120 --> 00:29:56,990
As they buffet South Georgia,
they also bring food.

208
00:29:59,280 --> 00:30:00,950
A seal carcass.

209
00:30:03,960 --> 00:30:06,630
A prize worth braving the surf for.

210
00:30:09,160 --> 00:30:12,830
Giant petrels are the vultures
of Antarctica

211
00:30:13,600 --> 00:30:15,950
and are always the first to the spoils.

212
00:30:30,080 --> 00:30:33,110
The word is out and the hordes move in.

213
00:30:45,720 --> 00:30:49,190
Like feathered dinosaurs,
they lock beaks in battle.

214
00:31:33,960 --> 00:31:38,990
These butchers provide a service
for some unlikely meat-eaters.

215
00:31:41,800 --> 00:31:46,310
With the carcasses now opened,
pintail ducks arrive for a meal.

216
00:31:50,880 --> 00:31:53,030
There's plenty of good food here

217
00:31:53,120 --> 00:31:55,590
and none of South Georgia's inhabitants

218
00:31:55,680 --> 00:31:59,150
can afford to be fussy
with winter looming.

219
00:32:05,920 --> 00:32:10,070
After the feast,
it's time for a rinse and spin.

220
00:32:20,680 --> 00:32:23,590
The breeding season is finally over

221
00:32:23,680 --> 00:32:26,750
and the petrels will
soon be heading out to sea

222
00:32:26,840 --> 00:32:29,390
to avoid the worst of the winter.

223
00:32:36,200 --> 00:32:40,150
A snowstorm is an omen
of things to come.

224
00:32:48,320 --> 00:32:50,470
There is now little left to eat

225
00:32:50,560 --> 00:32:55,990
and South Georgia's beaches will soon be
abandoned to the cold and ice.

226
00:33:05,600 --> 00:33:07,310
Further south still,

227
00:33:07,400 --> 00:33:11,830
and the first storms are
striking the continent of Antarctica.

228
00:33:33,160 --> 00:33:37,910
The AdÃ©lie penguins must rear
their half-grown chicks to adulthood

229
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:41,190
before winter hits
in just a few weeks' time.

230
00:33:45,920 --> 00:33:48,630
The chicks are only three weeks old.

231
00:33:48,720 --> 00:33:51,630
Their downy coats
aren't fully waterproof yet

232
00:33:51,720 --> 00:33:54,310
and they cluster together for warmth.

233
00:34:00,600 --> 00:34:03,830
