during bad weather,

234
00:34:03,920 --> 00:34:08,670
as most of the adults are away at sea
fishing for their fast-growing families.

235
00:34:17,800 --> 00:34:19,630
When the parents return,

236
00:34:19,720 --> 00:34:22,550
their offspring quickly leave
the comfort of their peers.

237
00:34:29,080 --> 00:34:31,790
Both chicks are ravenously hungry.

238
00:34:38,720 --> 00:34:41,870
But there may be only
enough food for one.

239
00:34:41,960 --> 00:34:47,830
This race could determine
which chick has the better prospects.

240
00:35:03,720 --> 00:35:09,710
Most AdÃ©lie pairs will only manage
to raise a single chick each season.

241
00:35:13,240 --> 00:35:16,190
And this may not be it.

242
00:35:22,520 --> 00:35:26,030
At least number one
is getting stronger by the day.

243
00:35:32,800 --> 00:35:36,750
With one meal delivered,
the parents must quickly find another.

244
00:35:48,520 --> 00:35:51,470
To rear their chicks
before the onset of winter,

245
00:35:51,560 --> 00:35:54,510
the penguins must work round the clock.

246
00:36:09,800 --> 00:36:14,790
The parents can travel over 100 miles
to reach the best fishing grounds

247
00:36:14,880 --> 00:36:17,430
and may be gone
for several days at a time.

248
00:36:29,520 --> 00:36:33,030
They return with a kilogram
of fish and squid in their bellies,

249
00:36:33,120 --> 00:36:34,310
feed their chicks

250
00:36:34,400 --> 00:36:37,590
and then go off again
to repeat the process.

251
00:36:44,280 --> 00:36:48,150
The job must be finished
before the sea freezes over again.

252
00:36:55,880 --> 00:36:57,510
At seven weeks old,

253
00:36:57,600 --> 00:37:00,870
the chicks are losing the last
of their baby down,

254
00:37:00,960 --> 00:37:03,830
and are now fully equipped
to take the plunge.

255
00:37:05,080 --> 00:37:07,510
Confidence is all that's lacking.

256
00:37:09,560 --> 00:37:13,070
Perhaps it'll help
if the parents lead by example.

257
00:37:21,200 --> 00:37:24,790
There. Effortless
and as graceful as any fish.

258
00:37:34,600 --> 00:37:38,590
It seems penguins are not born
with a love of water.

259
00:37:53,120 --> 00:37:56,470
Staying submerged is the next problem.

260
00:37:59,440 --> 00:38:03,070
Buoyancy control is clearly a skill
that needs practice.

261
00:38:13,240 --> 00:38:14,990
Well, it's a start.

262
00:38:17,440 --> 00:38:21,070
And at least
they can now reach the ice floes.

263
00:38:28,200 --> 00:38:31,230
Swimming is the first of many lessons.

264
00:38:31,720 --> 00:38:36,510
They must next learn
to recognise danger in all its forms.

265
00:39:03,440 --> 00:39:04,950
A leopard seal.

266
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:17,430
Even high up on an ice floe,
the penguins aren't safe.

267
00:39:20,240 --> 00:39:26,070
Each year, leopard seals will take
5, 000 of them from this colony alone.

268
00:39:34,040 --> 00:39:38,430
The AdÃ©lies that survive drift out
into the Southern Ocean.

269
00:39:55,560 --> 00:39:59,270
They will spend the next five months
feeding at sea,

270
00:39:59,360 --> 00:40:03,950
avoiding the great freeze
that is about to envelop Antarctica.

271
00:40:18,640 --> 00:40:24,150
The edge of the sea-ice advances
by up to two and a half miles a day.

272
00:40:32,760 --> 00:40:36,230
Eventually, over five million
square miles of ice

273
00:40:36,320 --> 00:40:38,710
will surround the continent
of Antarctica,

274
00:40:38,800 --> 00:40:41,070
effectively doubling its size.

275
00:40:49,040 --> 00:40:52,350
The great white wilderness is empty.

276
00:40:54,360 --> 00:40:55,990
But not for long.

277
00:41:09,440 --> 00:41:13,590
Bizarrely, it's now that
the emperor penguins arrive,

278
00:41:13,680 --> 00:41:16,430
just as all the other penguins
have left.

279
00:41:28,520 --> 00:41:31,310
These giants are now at their heaviest.

280
00:41:32,320 --> 00:41:36,630
They've been feeding at sea all summer
and can weigh 40 kilos.

281
00:41:59,720 --> 00:42:03,790
From the edge of the sea-ice,
they head towards their colony.

282
00:42:05,680 --> 00:42:09,630
But an obstacle course of
jumbled ice blocks stands in their way.

283
00:42:14,640 --> 00:42:18,150
The males are particularly fat
at this time of year.

284
00:42:20,680 --> 00:42:24,470
This will be crucial for
their survival in the months ahead,

285
00:42:24,560 --> 00:42:28,430
but it doesn't make squeezing
through narrow gaps any easier.

286
00:43:04,560 --> 00:43:06,790
With the worst behind them,

287
00:43:06,880 --> 00:43:11,510
they start a 20-mile march
into the freezer to breed,

288
00:43:12,400 --> 00:43:14,550
the only animals to do so.

289
00:43:24,960 --> 00:43:29,110
By tobogganing, they can travel
at twice their walking speed

290
00:43:29,200 --> 00:43:31,870
and it takes the weight off tired feet.

291
00:43:53,360 --> 00:43:57,350
Their destination is the thicker ice
closer to shore,

292
00:43:57,440 --> 00:44:01,150
which will stay solid long enough
for them to safely rear their chicks

293
00:44:01,240 --> 00:44:03,470
throughout the months to come.

294
00:44:11,840 --> 00:44:16,670
Their colony is in the lee of icebergs
trapped in the frozen ocean,

295
00:44:16,760 --> 00:44:20,070
which will shelter them
from the bitter Antarctic winds.

296
00:44:25,400 --> 00:44:28,670
Newly formed pairs promenade together.

297
00:44:45,640 --> 00:44:51,590
Courtship demands that both partners
strike and hold a variety of poses.

298
00:44:52,080 --> 00:44:53,630
It's an important process,

299
00:44:53,720 --> 00:44:58,270
as the bond between the couple will have
to be an exceptionally strong one.

300
00:45:10,080 --> 00:45:13,910
The final act lacks the elegance
of the prelude,

301
00:45:14,760 --> 00:45:16,710
but at least it's quick.

302
00:45:22,960 --> 00:45:25,430
The egg is laid a few days later.

303
00:45:25,760 --> 00:45:29,070
It contains the female's last reserves.

304
00:45:29,840 --> 00:45:31,870
She now has nothing more to give

305
00:45:31,960 --> 00:45:35,030
and must pass the egg to the male
to incubate.

306
00:45:40,960 --> 00:45:42,430
The couple must be quick.

307
00:45:42,520 --> 00:45:45,990
If the egg rests on the ice
for too long, it'll freeze.

308
00:45:51,400 --> 00:45:54,390
With their eggs safe in the care
of the males,

309
00:45:54,480 --> 00:45:58,430
the females start the long journey
back to the sea.

310
00:46:11,080 --> 00:46:16,230
The sun is also leaving
and will be gone for many months.

311
00:46:19,640 --> 00:46:22,990
The precious eggs,
balanced on the males' feet,

312
00:46:23,080 --> 00:46:26,790
will make the terrible ordeal ahead
worthwhile.

313
00:46:37,400 --> 00:46:40,750
With no food
and only each other for warmth,

314
00:46:40,840 --> 00:46:44,270
they will attempt
to keep the next generation alive

315
00:46:44,360 --> 00:46:48,150
while surviving
in the most brutal conditions on Earth.

316
00:46:51,040 --> 00:46:53,670
Not all of them will succeed.

317
00:46:58,960 --> 00:47:01,190
At both ends of our planet,

318
00:47:01,280 --> 00:47:04,430
the sun sets for the last time
in autumn.

319
00:47:06,840 --> 00:47:09,630
A season of change comes to an end

320
00:47:09,720 --> 00:47:13,830
and one of endless darkness
and bitter cold begins.

321
00:47:42,360 --> 00:47:45,030
The spectacular return
of the emperor penguins

322
00:47:45,120 --> 00:47:47,950
was a key event
for the Frozen Planet team.

323
00:47:55,160 --> 00:47:56,550
The crew will have to operate

324
00:47:56,640 --> 00:47:59,510
in the most dangerous
of all polar environments,

325
00:47:59,600 --> 00:48:01,590
the edge of the sea-ice.

326
00:48:03,400 --> 00:48:05,470
They have to fly in
everything they'll need

327
00:48:05,560 --> 00:48:08,350
for a month of living
on the frozen ocean.

328
00:48:12,760 --> 00:48:17,350
On board are slow-motion cameraman
John Aitchison,

329
00:48:17,880 --> 00:48:23,390
underwater cameraman Didier Noirot
and director Chadden Hunter.

330
00:48:26,400 --> 00:48:29,150
With the plane gone,
the team are on their own.

331
00:48:29,240 --> 00:48:31,550
This is home for the next month.

332
00:48:32,440 --> 00:48:34,310
But it doesn't look like much right now.

333
00:48:36,320 --> 00:48:39,670
Their tents should be secure
on the permanent sea-ice,

334
00:48:39,760 --> 00:48:43,550
but they're still miles from the ocean,
where they hope to film.

335
00:48:43,640 --> 00:48:45,550
The locals are keen to get acquainted

336
00:48:45,640 --> 00:48:48,630
with anything
of a familiar shape and size.

337
00:48:50,800 --> 00:48:53,950
The emperors are welcome neighbours
around the camp,

338
00:48:54,040 --> 00:48:56,790
but the team need to film them returning
from the water

339
00:48:56,880 --> 00:48:59,990
and to do that,
they face a daunting task.

340
00:49:00,520 --> 00:49:03,350
They must find a path to the open sea

341
00:49:03,440 --> 00:49:06,510
through a shifting landscape
of jagged sea-ice.

342
00:49:08,200 --> 00:49:11,030
Their first scouting trip
doesn't look promising.

343
00:49:11,120 --> 00:49:15,990
Neither maps nor sat-nav are any help
in this everchanging environment.

344
00:49:17,240 --> 00:49:20,510
The only clue that the ocean
lies somewhere to the east

345
00:49:20,600 --> 00:49:22,910
is a steady procession of penguins.

346
00:49:24,200 --> 00:49:25,270
Any suggestions, Didier?

347
00:49:25,360 --> 00:49:27,870
- We must find a way.
- Yes.

348
00:49:27,960 --> 00:49:29,870
And we will find a way.

349
00:49:30,640 --> 00:49:32,190
I like the attitude.

350
00:49:32,280 --> 00:49:34,110
The penguins have found a way.

351
00:49:34,600 --> 00:49:36,990
It seems the emperors
will be the key

352
00:49:37,080 --> 00:49:39,430
to reaching the ice edge.

353
00:49:39,560 --> 00:49:40,750
Okay, let's go.

354
00:49:42,480 --> 00:49:44,470
With their penguin guides
leading the way,

355
00:49:44,560 --> 00:49:48,630
snowmobiles are brought in
to haul 500 kilograms of equipment

356
00:49:48,720 --> 00:49:50,550
through the icy maze.

357
00:49:52,920 --> 00:49:56,710
It's tough going for film crew
and penguins.

358
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:02,710
When the ice ridges halt progress,
it's time for some back-breaking work.

359
00:50:09,760 --> 00:50:11,830
The next three days are spent chiselling

360
00:50:11,920 --> 00:50:14,590
through mile after mile
of broken sea-ice.

361
00:50:28,360 --> 00:50:32,470
Once finally clear of the ice boulders,
they spot their goal,

362
00:50:32,560 --> 00:50:35,790
a patch of open ocean with penguins.

363
00:50:42,720 --> 00:50:44,790
John is first in position.

364
00:50:44,880 --> 00:50:47,470
He hopes to capture
the most striking images

365
00:50:47,560 --> 00:50:50,990
by using a computerised
slow-motion camera.

366
00:50:52,960 --> 00:50:55,630
But attempts
to film the penguins underwater

367
00:50:55,720 --> 00:50:58,310
are halted by an unwelcome visitor.

368
00:50:58,680 --> 00:51:01,950
We just saw the head
of a massive leopard seal.

369
00:51:02,320 --> 00:51:05,150
So we'll get closer
to see what's going on.

370
00:51:06,480 --> 00:51:08,310
We must be careful, because those guys

371
00:51:08,400 --> 00:51:12,190
can come out very quickly
out of the hole and give a bite,

372
00:51:12,280 --> 00:51:16,430
but being red like that,
we should be quite protected, you know?

373
00:51:17,560 --> 00:51:21,430
Being dressed in red
may be Didier's idea of safety,

374
00:51:21,520 --> 00:51:25,590
but the rest of the crew have
a healthy respect for leopard seals.

375
00:51:26,040 --> 00:51:30,270
They can be fiercely territorial
and are not afraid to attack humans.

376
00:51:31,800 --> 00:51:34,630
I think I can run faster
than him on land.

377
00:51:35,560 --> 00:51:36,670
That's very exciting,

378
00:51:36,760 --> 00:51:40,950
that's the first time I've ever seen
a leopard seal in my life.

379
00:51:41,040 --> 00:51:45,750
And he's come straight out of the hole
and starts walloping towards us.

380
00:51:45,840 --> 00:51:47,990
So there's a lot of adrenaline.

381
00:51:48,840 --> 00:51:51,030
With the seal
frightening the penguins away

382
00:51:51,120 --> 00:51:55,470
and hassling the crew,
it's time to try a new hole.

383
00:52:02,120 --> 00:52:03,430
Oh, hello.

384
00:52:05,040 --> 00:52:06,630
Can you see him?

385
00:52:09,920 --> 00:52:11,150
While the seal is around,

386
00:52:11,240 --> 00:52:13,430
there's little hope
of filming the penguins.

387
00:52:13,520 --> 00:52:17,670
But now a far greater threat is posed
by the changing weather.

388
00:52:19,040 --> 00:52:21,790
That dark headland in the distance
is Cape Washington.

389
00:52:21,880 --> 00:52:24,870
That's our last sign of mainland.

390
00:52:24,960 --> 00:52:26,190
We can't see anything else.

391
00:52:26,280 --> 00:52:28,910
Once we lose sight of that mainland,

392
00:52:29,000 --> 00:52:32,870
that means we're out here
on our own on the sea-ice

393
00:52:32,960 --> 00:52:35,070
and this visibility is getting
lower and lower.

394
00:52:35,160 --> 00:52:38,830
It's started snowing
and this wind is just blowing off-shore,

395
00:52:38,920 --> 00:52:43,430
so if all this ice heads out,
we don't want to be on it.

396
00:52:44,040 --> 00:52:46,150
So I think we're going to
can filming for the day.

397
00:52:51,880 --> 00:52:56,550
All the signs suggest that
a big Antarctic storm is on its way.

398
00:52:59,960 --> 00:53:04,910
Winds pick up to 70 miles an hour
and everyone retreats to their tents.

399
00:53:08,120 --> 00:53:11,270
High winds then turn to heavy snow.

400
00:53:12,920 --> 00:53:16,990
On the driest continent on Earth,
a big snowfall is rare.

401
00:53:19,400 --> 00:53:23,790
White-out conditions take the penguins
and the film crew by surprise.

402
00:53:27,240 --> 00:53:30,550
Each day they must dig out
their buried equipment,

403
00:53:30,640 --> 00:53:32,710
filming has ground to a halt.

404
00:53:39,920 --> 00:53:44,750
One week and a metre of snow later,
the headland is visible again

405
00:53:44,840 --> 00:53:48,390
and the team are raring
to get back to the ice edge.

406
00:53:50,640 --> 00:53:53,510
They follow their old route
back through the frozen maze

407
00:53:53,600 --> 00:53:55,310
and with no leopard seal in sight,

408
00:53:55,400 --> 00:53:58,670
it's time for another attempt
with the pole cam.

409
00:54:00,720 --> 00:54:04,630
It's cumbersome, but it allows the team
to capture underwater images

410
00:54:04,720 --> 00:54:07,830
without having to risk
the icy water themselves.

411
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:12,590
- That is okay?
- That's perfect.

412
00:54:13,080 --> 00:54:15,710
They are coming, I can see some.

413
00:54:15,800 --> 00:54:19,030
Oh, wow.
Oh, penguin's coming in the hole.

414
00:54:19,120 --> 00:54:21,390
This is awesome, this is great.

415
00:54:21,800 --> 00:54:24,950
The aim now is
to film the penguins' dramatic exit

416
00:54:25,040 --> 00:54:26,310
from the hole.

417
00:54:26,400 --> 00:54:28,990
The only problem, which hole?

418
00:54:38,760 --> 00:54:41,510
These penguins keep outsmarting us.

419
00:54:41,600 --> 00:54:44,790
We tried to switch holes
to film them coming up

420
00:54:44,880 --> 00:54:47,790
and of course, they all just
completely came up behind us.

421
00:54:48,440 --> 00:54:49,950
Whatever the crew try,

422
00:54:50,040 --> 00:54:53,230
there's always someone
who hasn't read the script.

423
00:54:55,320 --> 00:54:56,710
John has been filming,

424
00:54:56,800 --> 00:55:01,510
but he can't view his slow-motion shots
until they are downloaded to a computer.

425
00:55:03,120 --> 00:55:06,510
While he waits,
Didier seizes his chance.

426
00:55:06,600 --> 00:55:08,390
Come, my friend, come.

427
00:55:08,720 --> 00:55:11,110
If you can't beat them, join them.

428
00:55:11,200 --> 00:55:15,230
It's time to go scuba diving
in the coldest waters on the planet.

429
00:55:15,320 --> 00:55:17,870
I will see you on the other side.

430
00:55:24,280 --> 00:55:26,510
The team are 300 miles from help

431
00:55:26,600 --> 00:55:30,350
and have only a small hole
as their lifeline to the surface.

432
00:55:35,360 --> 00:55:37,550
A magical world opens up.

433
00:55:37,920 --> 00:55:42,430
For the first time, Didier now shares
the penguins' perspective

434
00:55:42,520 --> 00:55:44,710
from beneath the ice.

435
00:55:59,240 --> 00:56:02,910
This is Antarctica
at its most enchanting.

436
00:56:05,280 --> 00:56:07,910
For Chadden, after weeks of struggle,

437
00:56:08,000 --> 00:56:11,470
the sequence quite literally
falls into his lap.

438
00:56:12,200 --> 00:56:14,150
Whoa!

439
00:56:14,440 --> 00:56:15,630
Sorry!

440
00:56:17,520 --> 00:56:19,470
I think I'm in the way.

441
00:56:24,480 --> 00:56:25,630
Up they go.

442
00:56:25,720 --> 00:56:29,070
Oh! Just a little...
Come this way. Here we go.

443
00:56:33,440 --> 00:56:37,030
I'm getting run over by penguins. Ooh!

444
00:56:37,800 --> 00:56:39,910
I think it worked.
It's very difficult to tell.

445
00:56:40,640 --> 00:56:43,190
John's camera
is finally capturing

446
00:56:43,280 --> 00:56:47,830
the super-slow-motion images
of the emperors' dramatic return.

447
00:56:51,200 --> 00:56:55,470
With the penguins performing perfectly,
it was all falling into place.

448
00:56:55,560 --> 00:56:58,870
The team were finally able
to capture Antarctica's

449
00:56:58,960 --> 00:57:01,470
most spectacular belly flop.

